[2] Preparedness and response

-Sat 1 Jun 2019. Uganda: Over USD 18 Million Spent to Prepare for Ebola Virus Disease [CGTN, abridged, edited]
https://newsaf.cgtn.com/news/3d3d774e776b7a6333566d54/index.html

The government of Uganda and partners have so far invested over USD 18 million in Ebola virus disease (EVD) preparedness and readiness. This was revealed at the just concluded Accountability Forum organized by the Ministry of Health at which partners shared information on their contribution in the EVD preparedness efforts in the country.

The funds have been utilized to implement various activities under the various pillars of the preparedness response, and significant progress has been made. For instance, under case management, 526 health workers in 14 districts have been trained on the appropriate handling of suspected EVD patients while taking sufficient protection measures for themselves. These health workers are now available for rapid deployment to any part of the country where EVD may occur.

Ebola Treatment Units (ETUs) have been constructed. 9806 health workers in 562 health units located in 11 high-risk districts of the Rwenzori sub-region have been trained and mentored on EVD Infection Prevention and Control (IPC).

In efforts to ensure further health workers' safety against EVD, 4419 frontline health workers in 13 districts have been vaccinated. EVD preparatory efforts have also been augmented with the training of 404 health workers in 13 districts on psychosocial support, and, in addition, 17 districts now have trained and fully equipped teams ready to conduct safe and dignified burials. For community education and awareness, over 2 million people have been reached through interpersonal communication and house to house visits using trained Village Health Teams (VHTs), civic leaders, religious and cultural leaders and volunteers. In the high-risk districts, over 12 000 people in these categories have been trained and deployed for this purpose.

--
