Sat 1 Jun 2019. Community Mobilization [Mercy Corps, abridged, edited]
https://www.mercycorps.org.uk/research/community-mobilization-essential-stopping-spread-ebola

The Ebola crisis in eastern Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) is worsening, and it poses a serious threat to the ongoing humanitarian response upon which nearly 13 million people depend for lifesaving aid. Despite the rapid spread of new infections, substantial community resistance to the response remains a serious obstacle, as indicated by persistent reports of individuals refusing the vaccine and recurring attacks on treatment centers.

Mercy Corps has published a new analysis, which demonstrates how community mobilization should be a central element to help stop the spread of Ebola in DRC and neighboring countries, taking lessons from Mercy Corps Ebola response in Liberia in 2014-2015 that reached over half of the population in that country. Over a 5-month period, Mercy Corps' community mobilization programmes led to substantial and rapid changes in behaviours and a deeper level of understanding about how to prevent the spread of Ebola.

--
Communicated by:
Mary Marshall

-31 May 2019. Butembo: Traditional chiefs ask for public support to eradicate Ebola outbreak in 30 days
[Crofs blog, abridged, edited]
https://crofsblogs.typepad.com/h5n1/2019/05/butembo-traditional-chiefs-ask-for-public-support-to-eradicate-ebola-outbreak-in-30-days.html

The traditional chiefs are determined to support the Ebola response teams with rites and sacrifices and to finish in the next 30 days. Nevertheless, eradication of the epidemic will be possible in the region [only] when the community is willing to collaborate with response teams in the fight against Ebola virus disease.

